datasets.name: EEG (Cleaned)
datasets.description_clean: Cleaned and downsampled EEG files for 42 participants About This Data Based on the raw EEG recordings that are publicly available, we further cleaned the EEG data during active task engagements with Automagic pipeline for ICA decomposition and classification. Then, data for each participants are further inspected in a manual process, to remove additional noisy components, interpolate bad channels and reject noisy time series. The cleaned EEG data were downsampled to 100Hz and saved in .set format compatible with EEGLab for redistribution. Access This Data The dataset is shared with public access via Figshare Plus (https://www.doi.org/10.25452/figshare.plus.29971873), containing 42 files named after the anonymised participant ID.

datasets.name: A multimodal human-computer interaction dataset for neurocognitive user state evaluation
datasets.description_clean: SENSE-42: A multimodal Human-Computer Interaction dataset from Simulated Environment for Neurocognitive User State Evaluation Overview SENSE-42 is a publicly available, multimodal dataset designed to support the study of user state monitoring during extended computer interaction sessions via neurocognitive, physiological and behavioural responses. Combining high-resolution neurophysiological recordings with behavioral and subjective data, this dataset enables research on the alternations of attention, mental/physical fatigue, cognitive workload, and related subjective indices at a very early stage. The dataset was collected from 42 participants over a 2-hour continuous interaction session, during which participants engaged in a series of designed tasks on a desktop computer with a mouse and keyboard. The experimental tasks were conducted within a fully simulated desktop operating system environment, designed to closely mimic real-world computer usage scenarios. This setup mirrors how people typically use computers in daily life. The simulated experiment program also enables the comprehensive capture of the mouse and keyboard data, synchronized with a high refresh rate monitor at 144 Hz. Recordings were collected in a noise-insulated room, minimizing external interruptions from the environment or the experimenter. The project includes both the raw dataset (available via Synapse) and the analysis codebase (available on GitHub, WIP) for replicability and reuse. Modalities and Data Contents The dataset includes multimodal signals across the following channels: Behavioural Data Participant interaction logs collected via PsychoPy, including task performance metrics, reaction times, and mouse & keyboard status per frame. Electroencephalography (EEG) 32-channel scalp EEG recordings collected with the BioSemi ActiveTwo system at 1024 Hz. EEG signals are stored in .bdf format. datasets.name: Neural Underpinnings of Attention in Children with NF1
datasets.description_clean: Neural Underpinnings of Attention in Children with NF1 Neural Underpinnings of Attention in Children with NF1 CTF Young Investigator Award Principal Investigator: Sara K. Pardej Project Lead / Data Coordinator: - Sara K. Pardej - Dr. Bonita P. Klein-Tasman - Dr. Christine L. Larson - Dr. Hanjoo Lee Institution: University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee Project Description: Attention difficulties are one of the most apparent aspects of the cognitive phenotype of neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), yet very little is known about the underlying neural mechanisms of attention in children with NF1. Children with NF1 have difficulties with various aspects of attention, including sustained, divided, shifting, visual, and auditory (Casnar & Klein-Tasman, 2017; Isenberg et al., 2013; North et al., 2002). While some children with NF1 show attention difficulties that meet criteria for Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD), there are also children whose difficulties do not meet that threshold but who nevertheless still demonstrate marked difficulties with sustained attention (Mautner et al., 2001) and planning (Hyman et al., 2005). Research in other populations, such as ADHD, has begun elucidating specific biomarkers of attention difficulties using electroencephalography (EEG) Event Related Potentials (ERPs). EEG is a relatively affordable and non-invasive imaging technique that can be used to further delineate neural mechanisms of attention difficulties. However, very few studies have used EEG methodology to examine the neural underpinnings of these attention difficulties in children with NF1. The goal of this research is to demonstrate the feasibility and promise of EEG approaches with school age children with NF1 to identify potential biomarkers of attention problems. While there is considerable variability in the behavioral phenotype of NF1, attention problems are commonly identified. There is a dearth of research about the neural underpinnings of these challenges, especially

datasets.name: StageEmo-VR Dataset
datasets.description_clean: StageEmo-VR Dataset Overview This dataset contains EEG, physiological signals, and behavioral data collected during a virtual reality (VR) emotion induction experiment. The study investigates emotional responses to VR video stimuli in both healthy controls and individuals with depression symptoms. Dataset Description - Name: StageEmo-VR: Multimodal Emotion Induction Dataset - Participants: 56 valid subjects (Note: Subject IDs are registration numbers only, not indicative of experimental order and cannot be used to identify individuals) - Groups: Healthy controls and individuals with depression symptoms (based on SDS scores) - BIDS Version: 1.9.0 - License: CC BY-NC 4.0 (with Data Use Agreement) Equipment - EEG System: Neuracle NeuroHub-W4 - EEG Cap: Neuracle 64-channel EEG Cap (Extended 10-20 system) - Channels: 59 EEG channels (after removing reference, ground, and EOG channels) - Original EOG Channels: 4 channels (HEOR, HEOL, VEOU, VEOL) - used for ICA artifact removal - Sampling Rate: 250 Hz (downsampled from original 1000 Hz) - Reference: Average reference (original online reference: AFz) - Ground: CPz Physiological Sensors - PPG: Photoplethysmography (blood volume pulse) - SPO2: Peripheral oxygen saturation - IMU: 9-axis inertial measurement unit (3-axis gyroscope, accelerometer, magnetometer) - Sampling Rate: 250 Hz (resampled to align with EEG) Modalities - EEG (electroencephalography) - Physiological signals (PPG, SPO2, IMU) - Behavioral data (reaction time, arithmetic quiz) - Self-report ratings (SAM, IPQ) Tasks - Baseline measurement (10s red cross fixation) - Context introduction (background information) - Video watching (10 runs with different emotional stimuli) - Post-video measurement Data Organization This dataset follows the Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) standard: StageEmo-VR/ ├── code/ Analysis code and tools ├── derivatives/ Processed/derived data │ ├── phenotype/ Phenotype data (ratings, behavior summaries) │ ├── qc/ Quality control reports

datasets.name: Iranian 6-11 years age population-based EEG, ERP, and cognition dataset
datasets.description_clean: Iranian 6-11 years age population-based EEG, ERP, and cognition dataset ------------------------------------------------------------------------- Principal Investigator Mohammad Ali Nazari Professor, Cognitive Neuroscience, Iran University of Medical Science, Tehran, IRAN @Alinazari Overview This dataset investigates neurodevelopmental profiles in children through EEG, ERP, and cognitive assessments. It includes data from 100 Iranian non-clinical participants aged 6–11 years (Mean = 8.52 ± 1.5 SD), drawn from a larger longitudinal study. The research, guided by the Research Domain Criteria (RDoC) framework, aims to improve diagnostic accuracy and intervention strategies for specific learning disabilities (SLD) using EEG/ERP measures and machine learning techniques. Cognitive assessments measured non-verbal intelligence (via the Raven Test), attention (IVA-2), and working memory. EEG recordings were taken during resting states (eyes closed/open) and working memory tasks involving numerical and non-numerical stimuli (ERP-based). Additional demographic and background information, such as age, gender, education, handedness, parental history of learning difficulties, and Child Symptom Inventory-4 (CSI-4) scores, were also collected. It provides valuable insights into childhood neurodevelopment, aiming to enhance children's cognitive and academic outcomes. Data Description Citation Nazari, M.A., Abbasi, S., Rezaeian, M. et al. datasets.name: Eye-BCI_multi_dataset
datasets.description_clean: Dataset Description The Eye-BCI multimodal dataset provides an extensive collection capturing simultaneous electroencephalography (EEG), electrooculogram (EOG), electromyogram (EMG), high-speed video recordings, and synchronized eye-tracking. Participants' mental states and selected physical characteristics are also included, creating a solid foundation for examining ocular artifacts and eye-movement features in Brain-Computer Interface (BCI) applications. Four experimental paradigms are recorded to elicit various sensory-motor responses and their influence on ocular activity: Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP), and P300 speller tasks. Within the P300 paradigm, trials are organized into two folders to differentiate word-length conditions, one for four-letter target words and the other for five-letter targets. Dataset information A detailed description of the dataset is available in the following paper: Guttmann-Flury, E., Sheng, X. & Zhu, X. Dataset combining EEG, eye-tracking, and high-speed video for ocular activity analysis across BCI paradigms. Sci Data 12, 587 (2025). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41597-025-04861-9 Participants A total of 31 volunteers, including both left- and right-handed individuals, participated in this experiment across 63 sessions, amounting to approximately 46 hours of recording. The dataset includes 2520 trials for each of the Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), and Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP) paradigms, and 5670 trials for the P300 paradigm. During the initial session, participants completed a questionnaire assessing their demographic information, physiological details, and psychophysiological states. Additionally, an a priori sample size calculation was performed to ensure adequate power for the analysis of signals related to blinks as well as cortical sources activated during the different paradigms^1^. datasets.name: BrainLat_dataset
datasets.description_clean: Dataset description The Latin American Brain Health Institute (BrainLat) dataset comprises multimodal neuroimaging data of 780 participants from Latin American. The dataset includes 530 patients with neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease (AD), behavioral variant frontotemporal dementia (bvFTD), multiple sclerosis (MS), Parkinson's disease (PD), and 250 healthy controls (HCs). This dataset (62.7 ± 9.5 years, age range 21–89 years) was collected through a multicentric effort across five Latin American countries to address the need for affordable, scalable, and available biomarkers in regions with larger inequities. The BrainLat dataset is the first regional collection of clinical and cognitive assessments, anatomical magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), resting-state functional MRI (fMRI), diffusion-weighted MRI (DWI), and high density resting-state electroencephalography (EEG) in dementia patients. In addition, it includes demographic information about harmonized recruitment and assessment protocols. The dataset is publicly available to encourage further research and development of tools and health applications for neurodegeneration based on multimodal neuroimaging, promoting the assessment of regional variability and inclusion of underrepresented participants in research. Individuals The BrainLat dataset contains neuroimaging and cognitive data from 780 subjects, including patients with AD (N =278), bvFTD (N =163), PD (N =57) and MS (N =32), and HCs (N =250). Recruitment centers Participants were enrolled in clinical sites from the Multi-Partner Consortium to Expand Dementia Research in Latin America (ReDLat), a regional effort to harmonize participant enrollment and neurocognitive assessment in multicentric studies. Five ReDLat countries were included (Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Mexico, and Peru). Dataset information A detailed description of the dataset can be found in Prado P, Medel V, Gonzalez-Gomez R, Sainz-Ballesteros A, Vidal V, Santamaría-Garc

datasets.name: Parkisons_BMDS
datasets.description_clean: Feature extraction for accelerometer-based Parkinson's diagnosis Ethan Goan, Sirinthip Roomkham, James Galloway, Dimitri Perrin School of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, Queensland University of Technology (QUT), Brisbane, Australia Summary Sentence Feature extraction from Regions Of Interest (ROIs) within accelerometer data to be used to detect the presence of Parkinson's Disease. Background/Introduction (suggested limit 200 words) The accelerometer data help us to understand the coordinate of the real world, in particular, for patients. These data can provide us an insight view of less periodic for Patients compared to the healthy subjects (Albert etl al., 2012). The motivation of our approach is to use off-the-shelf standard time and frequency domain features from accelerometer data. Most of the key features are derived from Albert et al. (2012), and other features including Hjorth activity, mobility and complexity. With the combination of these two types of features, our result provide a highly accurate prediction. Methods (suggested limit 800 words) First the accelerometer data is corrected using to quater-union rotation to transform the signal to real world coordinate system. ROIs are then found using the Short Time Fourier Transform (STFT). The STFT is used to find a windowed approximation of the power in the accelerometer data. By Parsevals theorem, the power of the accelerometer signal $$\(a(t) \)$$ is approximated by, $$ \begin{equation} P(t) = \sqrt{ \sum{f = 0}^{N-1} A(f,t) } \end{equation} $$ where $$\(f\)$$ is the frequency index, $$\(N\)$$ is the number of points used in the STFT and $$\(A(x,t)\)$$ is the STFT of the accelerometer signal. Locations where the approximated power is greater than a certain threshold are used to indicate ROIs where the subject is walking in the recorded data. This method allows for frequency selective power measures to be used, which could improve robustness to noise and additional movements in the recorded si

datasets.name: Tinnitus
datasets.description_clean: Welcome to NBML Tinnitus Dataset! "Tinnitus" dataset contains resting-state raw EEG data recorded from tinnitus patients at National Brain Mapping Laboratory (NBML), Tehran, Iran, using a 64 channel g.HIamp biosignal amplifier and acquisition/processing system (g.tec medical engineering, Austria) (http://www.gtec.at) with the electrodes positioned according to the international 10–10 system. Impedances of the active electrode system were kept below 50k ohms during recording. The EEG signals consisting of alternating 5-min eyes-closed and 5-min eyes-open, were recorded using right ear reference (A2) electrode, sampled at 1200Hz. - The folders "Subject1" to "Subject10" contain EEG data files (.mat) for 10 tinnitus patients. - The file "Electrodenumbers.xlsx" shows the electrode, which is related to each EEG channel. - The file "ChannelLocation.txt" shows the EEG channel locations. To download the dataset, please send a request email with your Synapse username to Fahimeh Mohagheghian (fahimeh.mohagheghian@uconn.edu). Please, cite our papers if you use our data in any publication: 1. Mohagheghian, F., et al., Altered effective brain network topology in tinnitus: An EEG source connectivity analysis. Biomedical Signal Processing and Control, 2021. 64: p. 102331. 2. Mohagheghian, F., et al., Computer-aided tinnitus detection based on brain network analysis of EEG functional connectivity. Journal of Biomedical Physics & Engineering, 2019. 9(6): p. 687.

datasets.name: FACED
datasets.description_clean: FACED: Finer-grained Affective Computing EEG Dataset Affective computing based on electroencephalogram (EEG) has gained increasing attention for its objectivity in measuring emotional states. While positive emotions play a crucial role in various real-world applications, such as human-computer interactions, the state-of-the-art EEG datasets have primarily focused on negative emotions, with less consideration given to positive emotions. Meanwhile, these datasets usually have a relatively small sample size, limiting exploration of the important issue of cross-subject affective computing. The proposed Finer-grained Affective Computing EEG Dataset (FACED) aimed to address these issues by recording 32-channel EEG signals from 123 subjects. datasets.description_clean: EEG alpha activity is the dominant oscillation in most adult humans, is highly heritable, and has been associated with a number of cognitive functions. Two EEG phenotypes, low- and high-voltage alpha (LVA & HVA), have been demonstrated to have high heritabilities. They have different prevalence depending on a population's ancestral origins. In the present study we assessed the influence of ancestry admixture on EEG alpha power, and conducted a whole genome sequencing association analysis and an ancestry-informed polygenic study on those phenotypes in a Native American (NA) population that has a high prevalence of LVA. Seven common variants, in LD with each other upstream from gene ASIC2, reached genome-wide significance (p = 2 × 10-8 ) having a positive association with alpha voltage. They had lower minor allele frequencies in the NAs than in a global population sample. Overall correlations between lower degrees of NA (higher degree European) ancestry and HVA, and higher degrees of NA and LVA were also found. Additionally a rare-variant gene-based study identified gene TIA1 being negatively associated with LVA. Approximately 3% of SNPs exhibited a 15-fold enrichment that explained nearly half of the total SNP-heritability for EEG alpha. These regions showed the most significant anti-correlations between NA ancestry and alpha voltage, and were enriched for genes and pathways mediating cognitive functions. Our findings suggested that these regions likely harbor causal variants for HVA, and lacking of such variants could explain the high prevalence of LVA in this NA population, possibly illuminating the ancestral origin and genetic basis for EEG alpha.
